r:role><gtr:name>PRINCIPAL_INVESTIGATOR</gtr:name></gtr:role><gtr:role><gtr:name>FELLOW</gtr:name></gtr:role></gtr:roles></gtr:personRole></gtr:personRoles><gtr:project url="http://gtr.ukri.org:80/projects?ref=ES%2FI03076X%2F1"><gtr:id>E11D5240-E414-4E7F-A16A-3D423BAD2658</gtr:id><gtr:title>India's Forgotten Citizens: Marginalisation, Aspirations and Agency among Urban Muslim Artisans</gtr:title><gtr:status>Closed</gtr:status><gtr:grantCategory>Fellowship</gtr:grantCategory><gtr:grantReference>ES/I03076X/1</gtr:grantReference><gtr:abstractText>&lt;p>Anthropologists have made significant contributions to understanding the lives and conditions of workers in India?s growing formal and informal economies. From the cultivation of class-based identities among informal workers (De Neve 2005) and the ?casualisation? (Breman 1996) and ?housewife-isation? (Mies 1982) of labour in the informal economy, to the growing body of sophisticated literature on industrial workshops (Cross 2007; Parry et al 1999), these studies have explored the diverse ways that workers engage with rapidly changing regimes of economic production. Yet despite this extensive scholarship, there has been surprisingly little focus on the lives and conditions of urban-based workers, an oversight that is especially acute with regard to Muslim communities that have historically resided in India?s cities. My research challenges this absence by providing detailed historical and ethnographic accounts, addressing:&lt;/p>

&lt;ol>
 

 &lt;li>processes of marginalisation resulting in the exclusion of urban Muslim artisans from projects of nation-building and subject-making&lt;/li>

 &lt;li>strategies artisans use to constitute themselves as subjects through ?performances of authenticity? in a context where Muslim artisans are denied the possibility of being authentic producers and their crafts are rapidly losing value and recognition.&lt;/li>

